# Minimal Comments

- Do not add large explanatory comments, banner comments, or long block comments in code files.
- Prefer self-explanatory code first; only add comments when they clarify non-obvious intent, constraints, or trade-offs.
- Keep comments short and local, usually one line or a very small block.
- Avoid narrating obvious code or restating the implementation.
- If extra explanation is useful, put it in the response to the user instead of in the source file.

Examples:

- Avoid:
  - multi-paragraph comments before helper functions
  - long "why this works" blocks for simple code
  - decorative section banners
- Prefer:
  - a brief note before tricky logic
  - a short warning near a constraint or workaround
